<!-- BACKGROUND -->
<tr valign=center>
<td bgcolor="FFCE00" colspan=2>
<font color=black face=arial,helvetica,geneva>
<b>Background</b></font>
</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2 valign=top background="paperbackground.JPG">
<br>
<UL>
<LI> This page is a summary of the site.
<LI> The announcement of a <a href=announce>solution</a>.
<LI> A brief <a href=what.html>statement</a> of the problem.
<LI> The <a href=kephistory.html>history</a> of the problem.<br>
<LI> A 1996 <a href=holyoke.html>lecture</a> at Mt. Holyoke
	explains the key ideas that will be involved in the proof.<br>
<LI> <a href="theprogram.html">
	Academic papers, popular articles,</a> and general reference
	books on discrete geometry.  
<LI>Ferguson's Ph.D. 
	<a href="samf/index.html">thesis</a> at the University
	of Michigan completes one of the five steps of the proof.<br>
<LI>Sean McLaughlin has proved Fejes T&oacute;th's
	<a href="dodec/index.html">
	dodecahedral conjecture</a><br>
<!--<LI> A <a href=glossary.html>glossary</a> of terms that are
	used at this site.<br>-->
<LI> Here is a link to the 
	<a href="http://www.math.lsa.umich.edu/~hales/kepler.html">
	old Kepler</a> conjecture page.
<LI> Follow this link to the 
	<a href="technical.html">serious stuff.</a>  This link is intended
	for discrete geometers who wish to check the technical details
	of the solution.
<LI> What have Kepler, Hilbert, Milnor, Coxeter, Fejes T&oacute;th
	and <a href=kepquotes.html>others said</a> about the Kepler Conjecture?
</UL>
 <br><br>
</td></tr>

